social_posts.post_text: Today I helped scatter the ashes of someone who I don’t have any photos with because we were friends in high school before cell phones and Instagram. He was one of the smartest people I ever knew but had a lot going against him as well as well as a lot of bad luck, and one of the saddest things that I've ever witnessed was a life that could have been positive and successful turn into a losing fight against alcohol, opioids, and other drugs. It's hard to post about in a way, but his adulthood didn't turn out to much other than a cautionary tale so I guess it should be told. All I can say is that what might look like relief from one kind of pain might be the door to something worse, so find help to face your demons head-on rather than try to medicate an escape from them. Our favorite movie was The Big Lebowski, so we went to the cliffs where they scattered Donnie and stopped at a bowling alley on the way home. RIP, Joseph Aims. No dog photo in this one. The mood isn’t right. Xo

GOALS! Thanks @tenerifebiketraining for getting me over to Europe next year. I haven't done much in Europe for Worst Retirement Ever, for a few reasons:
-If I was good enough to get those KOMs, I would still be in the WorldTour (that said, I still have the KOM from Montvernier that I got in 2017, which has survived several tours de France)
-Travel is expensive. I’ve found that I can make better stuff if I allow myself more time and don’t have to make a tight schedule around flights and car rentals and logistics
-It’s been done. You’ve seen Alpe d’Huez 1000 times. From a content perspective I’d much rather take my camera up Mt. Washington or Pikes Peak or Letras. 

But before I get too old, I do want to have a go at a few climbs over there. I’m excited because I’ve never been and @tenerifebiketraining has a great tour planned. As I make plans for another year of “Worst Retirement Ever,” I wonder if I’m getting too old for this. Then I look at certain performances which are undeniably as good as I’ve ever done. My 20s were full of fear and fury and desperation for survival in a roller-coaster pro racing environment, my 30s have been fueled more by love and gratitude. Any of those can be used for motivation, but I think part of how I’ve been able to extend it is that positivity burns cleaner. So thank you.

Next up on Worst Honeymoon Ever, @emialv did yoga on the beach with her friend @gilcelia, while I had a crack on the Col de la Madone. When you think about the most famous climbs, those KOMs were usually set during a grand tour when riders are fatigued and tactics are in play. 6 out of the top 10 here were from a race, but primarily this is the climb used for training, intervals, and power tests by the best in the world (over and over), making Madone I believe the hardest leaderboard on Earth (and @Strava doesn't do Mars). Evidence: to crack the top 10, you must beat a 4x Tour de France winner. I was just a couple seconds shy but the fastest in a couple years. 

Big thanks to @cottydale @thecolcollective and @dianakp06 @azurvelo for filming.

When you think of a super fancy, Michelin star restaurant like this one (@cellercanroca was rated the best in the world for many years), don’t compare it to other foods. Compare it to an art exhibit or a concert or a weekend getaway. It’s a team of professionals who’ve dedicated their lives to be the best at creating a full sensory experience, including taste, smell, setting, and service. I first went because I wanted a nice experience for my mom who was visiting after my dad passed away. I’ve noticed various drama from gravel and crit racing and even the Giro, where guys are yelling at each other to pull through in a breakaway, or someone didn’t do their fair share so shame on them for winning. In my 20s I followed the NRC which was about 35 race days a year, but the way I paid my bills was mostly from prize money at smaller events, where the top 10 would split $1000 in prize money. I won over 100 races against mostly amateurs all over the east coast, and 100% of them were out of breakaways because I was horrible sprinter. 

In a break, it’s all about who does the work on the front. If you sit on Mark Cavendish’s wheel while he pulls for 100 miles, you can beat him in a sprint. Racers know that, so you can’t let the other guy skip pulls if you want to win. How do you get someone to pull if they don’t want to? I handled it the same way it was done to me when I was coming up a few years before. First you try trickery: I’d tell a guy to “just pull for a couple minutes because I need a break while I eat this energy bar.” When he looked back I’d pretend I was chewing, and then I’d attack and never see him again. If that didn’t work there’d be yelling, cussing, name calling, bullying, and frankly—violence as you put someone right up to the curb. I got pushed around in dark parking lots a few times for something I said or did during a race, and I don’t blame them because I don’t like the person I had to be to get the job done. I’d take my $500 prize money and be off to another town to do it again.

I never figured out how to win races and also make friends, and the toxicity of that is what kept me from lining up at local races when I retired from the pros. These days, I don’t care who pulls at the group ride or the fondo, and if you beat me to the town line I’m proud of you. 

Real pros know that words are a tactic. They know where the line is, don’t take it personal, and pat each other on the back at the finish. Drama is good for clicks but it’s bad for the scene and bad for your health, and it doesn’t have to be that way.

I lost my favorite KOM yesterday: Mauna Kea on the Big Island of Hawaii. It was New Years Eve 2016, so technically my last day as a pro and super emotional for me. I’d just met @kevin (the founder of this here app) and he’d been training for it. Supported by @bigislandbiketours, you start at the beach, climb 14,000 ft from tropical weather to a wall of snow at the top. I was pushing hard but sharing it on Instagram live and taking photos, probably crying here and there. I stopped to poop at the visitors center, and then I was woefully upprepared for the 10k of dirt on my 28c tires and 25-tooth cassette. I ran it with my bike on my shoulder, got the KOM by 2 hours, and then went to down find Kevin to ride last section with him, witnessing one of the most determined and hard-working dudes of our generation dig deep to meet his goal. 

This is the ride that inspired me to do YouTube (and almost got me a TV show). This is the ride that saved me from a desk job. There’s so much to share on bikes that’s not races in Europe. I’ve done all kinds of insane rides and this one I think of every day. Someday I’ll get back to do it right (slower). Glad you got to “enjoy” it @warbasse. No doubt that you had similar adventures. 7 years was a good run to hold on to that crown. Thanks for the memory.
